Yes, your CSS looks correct for changing the background color and text color of an `input` element, as well as the color of its placeholder text.

Just a small correction - instead of writing `input ::placeholder`, you can write it as `input::placeholder`. There should be no space between `input` and `::placeholder`. Additionally, the `::placeholder` pseudo-element needs to be inside the `input` selector declaration like so:

```
input {
  background-color: #1e1e1e !important;
  color: #F5F5F5 !important;
}

input::placeholder {
  color: #F5F5F5 !important;
}
```

With these changes, your CSS should work as expected.

To change the color of an SVG image using CSS, you can use the `fill` property. The `fill` property applies a color to the interior of SVG shapes such as `<path>`, `<circle>`, `<rect>`, etc. Here's how you can use the `fill` property to change the color of an SVG image:

1. Add the SVG image to an HTML element, such as an `<img>` tag or by using it as a background image for an element.

2. Use CSS to target the SVG image and set the `fill` property to the desired color.

Here's an example of how to use the `fill` property to change the color of an SVG image that is used as a background image:

HTML:
```
<div class="icon"></div>
```

CSS:
```
.icon {
  background-image: url('path/to/your/svg/image.svg');
  background-size: contain;
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
  width: 50px;
  height: 50px;
}

.icon {
  fill: #FF0000; /* Change this to the desired color */
}
```

In this example, the `.icon` class is applied to a `div` element that uses an SVG image as its background image. The `fill` property is then used to change the color of the SVG image to red.

Note that the `fill` property only works for SVG images that are defined as vector shapes rather than raster images.

In CSS, you can use the `z-index` property to specify the "layering" order of elements. The `z-index` property controls the vertical stacking order of positioned elements that overlap each other, with higher values stacking above lower values. In order to use the `z-index` property, you need to set the `position` property on the elements to either `absolute`, `fixed`, or `relative`.

Here's an example of how to set a div on a different "layer" from other elements:

```
<div className="layered-element">
  This is a layered element
</div>

<style>
  .layered-element {
    position: absolute;
    z-index: 1;
    background-color: white;
  }

  /* other styles for the page */
  body {
    background-color: lightgray;
  }

  h1 {
    color: blue;
  }
</style>
```

In this example, the `.layered-element` div is positioned absolutely and given a `z-index` value of `1`. This means it is positioned above other elements that don't have a `z-index` value or have a lower value.

You can adjust the `z-index` value of different elements to move them up or down in the stacking order. Just remember that the `z-index` property only works on elements with a `position` value of `absolute`, `fixed`, or `relative`.

