```
<div class="inline-elements">
  <span>Element 1</span>
  <span>Element 2</span>
  <span>Element 3</span>
</div>

<style>
  .inline-elements {
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  .inline-elements span {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 10px;
    background-color: lightblue;
    margin-right: 10px;
    font-size: 20px;
  }
</style>
```

In this example, we have three `span` elements inside a `div` container. The `div` container is set to `white-space: nowrap`, which forces the `span` elements to stay in a single line. The `span` elements themselves are set to `display: inline-block`, so that they are treated as inline-level blocks, and given some padding, background color, right margin, and font size for styling.

With this setup, the `span` elements will stay in a single line and wrap horizontally only when the width of the container is too narrow to fit them all in one line.

